10
00:00:53,253 --> 00:00:55,421
narrator: when it comes to iconic hats, 

11
00:00:55,423 --> 00:00:57,890
nothing says french more than the beret,      

12
00:00:57,892 --> 00:01:00,592
specifically the basque-style beret,    

13
00:01:00,594 --> 00:01:03,295
as people wear different styles in other countries.   

14
00:01:03,297 --> 00:01:06,531
the basque beret was traditionally worn by shepherds

15
00:01:06,533 --> 00:01:09,601
tending their flocks along the pyrenees mountain range  

16
00:01:09,603 --> 00:01:14,105
that divides southern france from spain.       

17
00:01:14,107 --> 00:01:18,310
the basque beret dates back  
to the 1600s in southern france.

18
00:01:18,312 --> 00:01:22,481
made of black merino wool,   
it has a little cabillou on top.

19
00:01:22,483 --> 00:01:27,286
the factory making these berets
has been doing so since 1840. 

20
00:01:27,288 --> 00:01:31,924
an automated machine knits   
undyed wood yarn into a galette,

21
00:01:31,926 --> 00:01:34,125
the french word for pancake.  

22
00:01:34,127 --> 00:01:36,862
the galette is flat and round with loose      

23
00:01:36,864 --> 00:01:41,967
knit stitches making it soft and floppy.        

24
00:01:41,969 --> 00:01:45,237
a worker then pulls the galette's central thread, 

25
00:01:45,239 --> 00:01:48,841
closing it into a circular shape
resembling a shower cap.    

26
00:01:48,843 --> 00:01:51,644
♪♪         

27
00:01:51,646 --> 00:01:54,246
in an industrial size washing machine,        

28
00:01:54,248 --> 00:01:58,283
a worker washes this rudimentary
beret in lukewarm water    

29
00:01:58,285 --> 00:02:02,855
from the local river and soap for about 8 hours.  

30
00:02:02,857 --> 00:02:05,490
the type of soap is a trade secret.       

31
00:02:05,492 --> 00:02:06,759
the wool shrinks,       

32
00:02:06,761 --> 00:02:09,762
causing the loose knit stitches
to tighten.          

33
00:02:09,764 --> 00:02:12,364
the wool fibers also soften,  

34
00:02:12,366 --> 00:02:15,067
transforming into the smooth and soft wool    

35
00:02:15,069 --> 00:02:18,404
and fabric we call felt.    

36
00:02:18,406 --> 00:02:19,872
after felting the beret,    

37
00:02:19,874 --> 00:02:23,141
the manufacturers begin the dyeing process.      

38
00:02:23,143 --> 00:02:25,877
the worker loads it into another washing machine,    

39
00:02:25,879 --> 00:02:28,814
only this time with powdered dye.       

40
00:02:28,816 --> 00:02:31,450
this factory has always produced its own dyes     

41
00:02:31,452 --> 00:02:33,819
in a wide range of colors,   

42
00:02:33,821 --> 00:02:36,822
again using water from the local river.     

43
00:02:36,824 --> 00:02:39,224
however, the temperature to which this company heats  

44
00:02:39,226 --> 00:02:41,627
it is a closely guarded secret.

45
00:02:41,629 --> 00:02:47,699
♪♪         

46
00:02:47,701 --> 00:02:50,602
when the dye cycle finishes, another worker checks     

47
00:02:50,604 --> 00:02:53,172
the beret against a color sample

48
00:02:53,174 --> 00:02:56,574
because the wool composition and the river water quality  

49
00:02:56,576 --> 00:02:59,612
are variable factors that can affect dye absorption.

50
00:02:59,614 --> 00:03:02,481
♪♪         

51
00:03:02,483 --> 00:03:06,351
the next step is to form the beret to the final shape. 

52
00:03:06,353 --> 00:03:11,123
traditionally, beret factories did this using wooden forms,  

53
00:03:11,125 --> 00:03:14,660
but today, they use metal ones.

54
00:03:14,662 --> 00:03:16,995
the beret remains on the form long enough          

55
00:03:16,997 --> 00:03:19,364
to lock in the shape.     

56
00:03:19,366 --> 00:03:22,467
this process, too, depends on the wool composition      

57
00:03:22,469 --> 00:03:23,736
as well as on how humid    

58
00:03:23,738 --> 00:03:26,138
it is in the factory on that particular day.    

59
00:03:26,140 --> 00:03:30,742
♪♪         

60
00:03:30,744 --> 00:03:34,413
each beret goes for a spin on the scratching machine,   

61
00:03:34,415 --> 00:03:38,149
a rotating wheel surfaced with wire brushes.       

62
00:03:38,151 --> 00:03:41,453
the bristles lift the wood fibers, thickening the felt.  

63
00:03:41,455 --> 00:03:46,658
♪♪         

64
00:03:46,660 --> 00:03:50,462
after inserting a cardboard template to maintain the shape,

65
00:03:50,464 --> 00:03:52,831
a worker uses a manual shearing tool         

66
00:03:52,833 --> 00:03:56,535
to carefully scratch the area around the cabillou.      

67
00:03:56,537 --> 00:04:00,038
she removes any clinging plant debris left by the river water 

68
00:04:00,040 --> 00:04:03,641
used in the wash and dye cycles.

69
00:04:03,643 --> 00:04:06,678
then she inspects for any holes
or stretched fibers.      

70
00:04:06,680 --> 00:04:09,748
♪♪         

71
00:04:09,750 --> 00:04:13,952
the beret now goes to the seamstress.       

72
00:04:13,954 --> 00:04:17,556
first, she heats a black cotton
lining on a mold to shape it  

73
00:04:17,558 --> 00:04:20,793
to fit perfectly inside the beret.       

74
00:04:20,795 --> 00:04:22,895
the lining has the manufacturer's label    

75
00:04:22,897 --> 00:04:24,362
in the center,         

76
00:04:24,364 --> 00:04:29,034
which features the company crest
and the model name, vrai basque,

77
00:04:29,036 --> 00:04:32,838
confirming that this is indeed 
an authentic basque-style beret.

78
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:36,675
♪♪         

79
00:04:36,677 --> 00:04:39,978
she turns the beret inside out to sew in the lining.     

80
00:04:39,980 --> 00:04:46,584
♪♪         

81
00:04:46,586 --> 00:04:49,288
then she turns the beret right side out again      

82
00:04:49,290 --> 00:04:52,190
and puts it on a stretching machine.     

83
00:04:52,192 --> 00:04:54,993
she sets the machine to the desired hat size,    

84
00:04:54,995 --> 00:04:58,263
and it automatically stretches the beret to that size.    

85
00:04:58,265 --> 00:05:04,636
♪♪         

86
00:05:04,638 --> 00:05:08,240
now, she sews a black leather band to the edge.   

87
00:05:08,242 --> 00:05:10,509
the hat size is printed on it. 

88
00:05:10,511 --> 00:05:12,978
some models feature a color trim on the band.   

89
00:05:12,980 --> 00:05:16,815
♪♪         

90
00:05:16,817 --> 00:05:19,951
the finishing touch is the company's metal hallmark. 

91
00:05:19,953 --> 00:05:23,021
♪♪         

92
00:05:23,023 --> 00:05:26,058
she rivets it to the underside of the beret on one side...  

93
00:05:26,060 --> 00:05:32,064
♪♪         

94
00:05:32,066 --> 00:05:35,000
...and that caps off production.

95
00:05:35,002 --> 00:05:40,472
♪♪         

96
00:05:47,314 --> 00:05:52,818
♪♪         

97
00:05:52,820 --> 00:05:54,820
narrator: pastis is an anise-flavored liqueur   

98
00:05:54,822 --> 00:05:56,721
popular in france,       

99
00:05:56,723 --> 00:05:59,258
particularly in the southern city of marseilles       

100
00:05:59,260 --> 00:06:01,059
where it originated.      

101
00:06:01,061 --> 00:06:02,527
you don't drink it straight, though.      

102
00:06:02,529 --> 00:06:05,297
the proper technique is to dilute it with water,    

103
00:06:05,299 --> 00:06:08,733
typically 5 to 7 parts water to one part pastis.   

104
00:06:08,735 --> 00:06:13,638
then add ice.         

105
00:06:13,640 --> 00:06:16,708
the maker of this pastis combines star anise      

106
00:06:16,710 --> 00:06:19,311
with licorice extract and herbs and spices      

107
00:06:19,313 --> 00:06:22,881
from the provence region of france.       

108
00:06:22,883 --> 00:06:26,585
star anise is an asian spice. 

109
00:06:26,587 --> 00:06:28,821
the starting ingredient for this pastis is       

110
00:06:28,823 --> 00:06:31,823
a pale yellow star anise essential oil         

111
00:06:31,825 --> 00:06:36,929
purchased from a chinese supplier.    

112
00:06:36,931 --> 00:06:39,998
the first step at this french distillery is to distill    

113
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,134
that essential oil.      

114
00:06:42,136 --> 00:06:43,535
as the oil is heated,     

115
00:06:43,537 --> 00:06:46,571
it evaporates and rises up the column still,       

116
00:06:46,573 --> 00:06:49,975
passing through a series of stacking cooling trays.   

117
00:06:49,977 --> 00:06:51,376
each tray condenses,      

118
00:06:51,378 --> 00:06:55,781
then removes one of the oil's various components.      

119
00:06:55,783 --> 00:06:59,584
pastis requires just one of the extracted components --  

120
00:06:59,586 --> 00:07:02,921
anethole, which is an organic compound responsible      

121
00:07:02,923 --> 00:07:07,059
for the anise flavor and smell.

122
00:07:07,061 --> 00:07:12,196
this pastis recipe also contains
60 different herbs and spices, 

123
00:07:12,198 --> 00:07:17,970
each of which is separately distilled into alcohol.    

124
00:07:17,972 --> 00:07:20,973
one of these herbs is artemisia vulgaris,     

125
00:07:20,975 --> 00:07:25,510
commonly known as mugwort.   

126
00:07:25,512 --> 00:07:27,980
a worker loads mugwort leaves into a tank       

127
00:07:27,982 --> 00:07:30,649
filled with a mixture of water and alcohol.     

128
00:07:30,651 --> 00:07:38,489
♪♪         

129
00:07:38,491 --> 00:07:42,327
as the leaves soak, the alcohol acts as a solvent, 

130
00:07:42,329 --> 00:07:45,364
extracting the aromatic molecules.    

131
00:07:45,366 --> 00:07:49,467
this process is called maceration.     

132
00:07:49,469 --> 00:07:53,138
after a few days, workers drain the alcoholic liquid,  

133
00:07:53,140 --> 00:07:56,808
now infused with aromatic molecules.      

134
00:07:56,810 --> 00:08:02,246
it's so alcoholic that it emits volatile fumes,    

135
00:08:02,248 --> 00:08:04,249
so workers wear an alarm that goes off         

136
00:08:04,251 --> 00:08:08,453
when the surrounding air reaches an explosive level.  

137
00:08:08,455 --> 00:08:09,854
the liquid is stored in a vat 

138
00:08:09,856 --> 00:08:13,225
until it's time to mix the pastis.       

139
00:08:13,227 --> 00:08:16,294
then, a worker removes the alcohol-soaked mugwort   

140
00:08:16,296 --> 00:08:17,595
leaves from the tank      

141
00:08:17,597 --> 00:08:20,431
and transfer them to a distillation device    

142
00:08:20,433 --> 00:08:23,668
called an alembic.       

143
00:08:23,670 --> 00:08:26,939
the alembic heats the mash of fermented leaves with steam 

144
00:08:26,941 --> 00:08:31,777
produced by a wood-fired boiler.

145
00:08:31,779 --> 00:08:33,945
once the mash heats to a temperature of        

146
00:08:33,947 --> 00:08:35,814
172 degrees fahrenheit,    

147
00:08:35,816 --> 00:08:41,553
the alcohol in it begins to evaporate and rise. 

148
00:08:41,555 --> 00:08:45,923
the alcoholic vapor eventually 
reaches the neck of the alembic,

149
00:08:45,925 --> 00:08:48,526
where cooling coils condense it into liquid,    

150
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:51,830
which then flows out of    
the alembic and through a filter

151
00:08:51,832 --> 00:08:54,833
that also removes plant particles.        

152
00:08:54,835 --> 00:08:58,036
an alcoholometer measures the percentage of alcohol,   

153
00:08:58,038 --> 00:09:01,906
which starts off very high, then tapers off.        

154
00:09:01,908 --> 00:09:04,942
the pastis maker uses only the middle of the flow,  

155
00:09:04,944 --> 00:09:08,513
when the reading is between 70 and 50%,          

156
00:09:08,515 --> 00:09:12,517
what's known as the heart of the distillation.      

157
00:09:12,519 --> 00:09:16,888
to make the pastis, workers combine all the ingredients.  

158
00:09:16,890 --> 00:09:20,225
the anethole, distilled from the anise essential oil,    

159
00:09:20,227 --> 00:09:22,894
the 60 different maceration liquids and distillates of   

160
00:09:22,896 --> 00:09:26,765
herbs and spices and licorice extract.     

161
00:09:26,767 --> 00:09:30,168
workers also add water to dilute
the final product's      

162
00:09:30,170 --> 00:09:33,638
alcohol level to 45%.     

163
00:09:33,640 --> 00:09:35,974
a last filtration removes any particles     

164
00:09:35,976 --> 00:09:40,511
that would diminish the clarity of the pastis.   

165
00:09:40,513 --> 00:09:43,115
a machine bottles the pastis in dark glass         

166
00:09:43,117 --> 00:09:45,317
to protect the contents from light,          

167
00:09:45,319 --> 00:09:48,053
which, by oxidation, would damage the liqueur.   

168
00:09:48,055 --> 00:09:52,256
♪♪         

169
00:09:52,258 --> 00:09:53,759
the second station on the filling line        

170
00:09:53,761 --> 00:09:56,728
seals each bottle with a t-cork,

171
00:09:56,730 --> 00:09:58,796
a type of stopper designed for bottles      

172
00:09:58,798 --> 00:10:03,735
which are opened and sealed repeatedly.     

173
00:10:03,737 --> 00:10:06,705
the next station applies a sheath of heat shrink plastic

174
00:10:06,707 --> 00:10:09,574
over the t-cork.        

175
00:10:09,576 --> 00:10:12,144
the bottle then travels through a heating tunnel,   

176
00:10:12,146 --> 00:10:13,879
which shrinks the plastic tightly      

177
00:10:13,881 --> 00:10:15,446
over the neck of the bottle.  

178
00:10:15,448 --> 00:10:19,584
♪♪         

179
00:10:19,586 --> 00:10:23,155
the final station applies the adhesive-backed label.   

180
00:10:23,157 --> 00:10:29,761
♪♪         

181
00:10:29,763 --> 00:10:32,564
pastis is always poured into the glass first,     

182
00:10:32,566 --> 00:10:36,768
followed by water.       

183
00:10:36,770 --> 00:10:38,703
this makes the liqueur cloudy 

184
00:10:38,705 --> 00:10:43,408
because the anethole doesn't dissolve in water.   

185
00:10:43,410 --> 00:10:47,979
if you want to add ice, you can
do so only after the water,  

186
00:10:47,981 --> 00:10:50,916
otherwise, the anethole crystallizes.         

187
00:10:50,918 --> 00:10:54,319
so just remember that chemistry lesson and enjoy.  

188
00:10:54,321 --> 00:10:58,256
♪♪         

189
00:11:05,098 --> 00:11:08,900
♪♪         

190
00:11:08,902 --> 00:11:11,469
narrator: the first stationary bike   

191
00:11:11,471 --> 00:11:13,437
was developed by a london physician       

192
00:11:13,439 --> 00:11:15,373
in the late 18th century    

193
00:11:15,375 --> 00:11:18,643
to exercise the joints of patients suffering from gout, 

194
00:11:18,645 --> 00:11:21,980
rheumatic disorders, or other afflictions.     

195
00:11:21,982 --> 00:11:24,816
the modern stationary bike is all about helping people  

196
00:11:24,818 --> 00:11:27,652
stay fit to prevent illnesses. 

197
00:11:27,654 --> 00:11:31,223
♪♪         

198
00:11:31,225 --> 00:11:35,193
on this stationary bike, magnets linked to the flywheel 

199
00:11:35,195 --> 00:11:38,964
create tension that causes the cyclist to push harder,  

200
00:11:38,966 --> 00:11:43,568
making the workout truly an uphill battle.    

201
00:11:43,570 --> 00:11:47,438
production starts with steel tubing for the base.   

202
00:11:47,440 --> 00:11:50,541
a probe locates the center of the tubing.         

203
00:11:50,543 --> 00:11:54,012
this reference point allows a computerized laser cutter  

204
00:11:54,014 --> 00:11:58,216
to find the exact spots to cut assembly holes.     

205
00:11:58,218 --> 00:12:00,117
with the assembly holes cut,  

206
00:12:00,119 --> 00:12:03,721
the laser slices the tubing to the correct length.     

207
00:12:03,723 --> 00:12:06,124
an automated system retrieves the part       

208
00:12:06,126 --> 00:12:10,295
and transfers it to a holding area.       

209
00:12:10,297 --> 00:12:13,031
a worker inserts screws in the base part,       

210
00:12:13,033 --> 00:12:16,234
which will attach it to the main frame.       

211
00:12:16,236 --> 00:12:21,439
he pipes sealant around the screws.       

212
00:12:21,441 --> 00:12:24,809
another worker now arranges the three tubular base parts  

213
00:12:24,811 --> 00:12:30,148
in a welding fixture and clamps them in place.   

214
00:12:30,150 --> 00:12:34,719
the fixture revolves and meets up with a robotic welder.   

215
00:12:34,721 --> 00:12:38,756
the robot welds the three parts together.   

216
00:12:38,758 --> 00:12:42,794
this completes the base of the stationary bike.    

217
00:12:42,796 --> 00:12:45,697
the bike's main frame has been configured on the other side  

218
00:12:45,699 --> 00:12:47,465
of the welding fixture.    

219
00:12:47,467 --> 00:12:50,368
the robot welds these parts together.     

220
00:12:50,370 --> 00:12:53,337
the fixture rotates to serve up
another base assembly     

221
00:12:53,339 --> 00:12:54,672
to the robot,         

222
00:12:54,674 --> 00:12:56,808
and the worker collects the welded main frame     

223
00:12:56,810 --> 00:13:00,378
from the reverse side.     

224
00:13:00,380 --> 00:13:02,780
he grinds the welded seam smooth

225
00:13:02,782 --> 00:13:06,518
and gets rid of burrs on the steel.         

226
00:13:06,520 --> 00:13:11,923
workers sandblast the metal, wash it, and apply primer.   

227
00:13:11,925 --> 00:13:15,059
after grounding the main frame,
another worker sprays     

228
00:13:15,061 --> 00:13:18,763
electrostatically charged resin and pigment onto it.   

229
00:13:18,765 --> 00:13:21,766
once it's baked on, this powder coat will provide 

230
00:13:21,768 --> 00:13:24,202
a protective finish.      

231
00:13:24,204 --> 00:13:28,573
at another station, a 55-ton press punches holes into posts 

232
00:13:28,575 --> 00:13:31,576
for the bike's handlebar and seat.      

233
00:13:31,578 --> 00:13:37,382
the holes are for adjusting the height of these parts.   

234
00:13:37,384 --> 00:13:39,517
next up is the casting for mounting          

235
00:13:39,519 --> 00:13:42,053
the handlebar to the post.   

236
00:13:42,055 --> 00:13:43,654
using another press,      

237
00:13:43,656 --> 00:13:48,393
the worker entrenches the top of the post in the casting.  

238
00:13:48,395 --> 00:13:50,728
he taps the casting with a rubber mallet      

239
00:13:50,730 --> 00:13:56,334
to tweak the installation and sets the assembly aside.  

240
00:13:56,336 --> 00:13:59,838
at another station, a worker arranges numerous seat posts  

241
00:13:59,840 --> 00:14:02,306
in tight alignment.      

242
00:14:02,308 --> 00:14:04,309
he drapes a stencil of sequential         

243
00:14:04,311 --> 00:14:07,978
lettering on top of the posts. 

244
00:14:07,980 --> 00:14:10,815
he dips an etching wand in a chemical solution     

245
00:14:10,817 --> 00:14:14,786
and then moves it over the letters five times.    

246
00:14:14,788 --> 00:14:17,055
this burns the letters into the steel,        

247
00:14:17,057 --> 00:14:21,559
providing markers for height adjustment.     

248
00:14:21,561 --> 00:14:23,794
an assembler drives the wedge into one of the bike's     

249
00:14:23,796 --> 00:14:29,200
two crank arms to create a hole
that the axle will fit into.  

250
00:14:29,202 --> 00:14:32,637
he checks the depth of the hole
with a gauge.         

251
00:14:32,639 --> 00:14:35,540
he inserts the end of the axle in the hole    

252
00:14:35,542 --> 00:14:40,812
and using a press, pushes it into place.     

253
00:14:40,814 --> 00:14:43,715
he measures the hole from the other side of the crank arm

254
00:14:43,717 --> 00:14:46,818
and confirms that the axle has been set to the correct depth. 

255
00:14:46,820 --> 00:14:50,822
♪♪         

256
00:14:50,824 --> 00:14:55,927
he then bolts the assembly to a precise torque.      

257
00:14:55,929 --> 00:14:59,764
he locks the crank arm assembly in a lathe.      

258
00:14:59,766 --> 00:15:02,834
he slips a foam sleeve over the axle to protect it  

259
00:15:02,836 --> 00:15:05,770
from shards of flying metal as a tool machines       

260
00:15:05,772 --> 00:15:07,238
the part of the crank arm   

261
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:09,641
that will ultimately hold the bike's pulley.    

262
00:15:09,643 --> 00:15:14,979
♪♪         

263
00:15:14,981 --> 00:15:17,415
another member of the team now assembles bearings     

264
00:15:17,417 --> 00:15:19,417
to a wheel hub.        

265
00:15:19,419 --> 00:15:22,220
he slides two bearings with a spacer in a press.   

266
00:15:22,222 --> 00:15:25,657
♪♪         

267
00:15:25,659 --> 00:15:30,428
he heats the hub in an oven, causing the metal to expand.  

268
00:15:30,430 --> 00:15:33,732
the machine presses the hub sandwich together.   

269
00:15:33,734 --> 00:15:38,836
as the hub cools, it shrinks  
for a tight fit to the bearings.

270
00:15:38,838 --> 00:15:40,771
he installs a retaining clip in the hub           

271
00:15:40,773 --> 00:15:43,941
to also keep it together.   

272
00:15:43,943 --> 00:15:46,144
next up are the holders for the magnets        

273
00:15:46,146 --> 00:15:49,047
that create resistance on the flywheel.        

274
00:15:49,049 --> 00:15:50,581
a worker places each one    

275
00:15:50,583 --> 00:15:53,952
in a fixture to inspect the dimensions.   

276
00:15:53,954 --> 00:15:58,990
he then checks the strength of the magnets in a tester,  

277
00:15:58,992 --> 00:16:02,360
and satisfied, he inserts two in each holder. 

278
00:16:02,362 --> 00:16:05,062
♪♪         

279
00:16:05,064 --> 00:16:08,265
this metal cage, pulled into position by the magnets,    

280
00:16:08,267 --> 00:16:10,935
completes the magnetic field. 

281
00:16:10,937 --> 00:16:12,470
stay tuned for more      

282
00:16:12,472 --> 00:16:15,006
on the making of this stationary bike.     

283
00:16:21,748 --> 00:16:26,817
♪♪         

284
00:16:26,819 --> 00:16:28,286
narrator: stationary bikes are equipped 

285
00:16:28,288 --> 00:16:30,321
with resistance mechanisms.  

286
00:16:30,323 --> 00:16:34,392
they can be simple tension belts
or more complex systems in which

287
00:16:34,394 --> 00:16:38,563
magnets produce an electrical current in the flywheel.    

288
00:16:38,565 --> 00:16:41,632
the indoor cyclist simply dials up the resistance,    

289
00:16:41,634 --> 00:16:43,734
and he or she will soon feel the burn.      

290
00:16:43,736 --> 00:16:48,039
♪♪         

291
00:16:48,041 --> 00:16:51,309
the assembler installs the magnetic resistance unit  

292
00:16:51,311 --> 00:16:54,746
so that it swings from a bracket on the main frame.  

293
00:16:54,748 --> 00:16:59,083
this bracket also holds the computer board.      

294
00:16:59,085 --> 00:17:01,719
he mounts the aluminum flywheel to the axle,     

295
00:17:01,721 --> 00:17:05,356
sliding it between the magnets and the tension device.    

296
00:17:05,358 --> 00:17:09,226
he caps the flywheel hub    
and secures the cap with screws.

297
00:17:09,228 --> 00:17:11,830
♪♪         

298
00:17:11,832 --> 00:17:13,330
the torsion spring-equipped  

299
00:17:13,332 --> 00:17:16,467
cover completes the stationary bike's tension system.     

300
00:17:16,469 --> 00:17:19,737
♪♪         

301
00:17:19,739 --> 00:17:23,007
he assembles the crank arm and axle to the bike      

302
00:17:23,009 --> 00:17:24,942
and installs a bearing.    

303
00:17:24,944 --> 00:17:28,712
then the bike moves on to the next station.      

304
00:17:28,714 --> 00:17:30,548
another worker places an alignment tool       

305
00:17:30,550 --> 00:17:33,250
on the back axle.       

306
00:17:33,252 --> 00:17:36,721
he loops an elastic belt with grooves around the small pulley

307
00:17:36,723 --> 00:17:38,022
on the flywheel        

308
00:17:38,024 --> 00:17:41,926
and around the larger crank arm pulley, linking the two.  

309
00:17:41,928 --> 00:17:45,329
he inserts another tool into the crank arm and turns it   

310
00:17:45,331 --> 00:17:50,167
to better wrap the belt around the large crank pulley. 

311
00:17:50,169 --> 00:17:52,536
he then removes both installation tools.      

312
00:17:52,538 --> 00:17:56,173
♪♪         

313
00:17:56,175 --> 00:18:00,111
he installs four flat bushings in the handlebar post.     

314
00:18:00,113 --> 00:18:02,513
these bushings make it possible
for the handlebar       

315
00:18:02,515 --> 00:18:05,416
to be raised and lowered.   

316
00:18:05,418 --> 00:18:09,320
he applies a decal with the height indicators.  

317
00:18:09,322 --> 00:18:11,456
made of a rugged synthetic material,      

318
00:18:11,458 --> 00:18:15,259
the decal encases three sides of the metal post,    

319
00:18:15,261 --> 00:18:17,495
and this protects it from abrasion.         

320
00:18:17,497 --> 00:18:21,933
♪♪         

321
00:18:21,935 --> 00:18:25,236
he bolts the second crank arm to the axle          

322
00:18:25,238 --> 00:18:27,539
and torques it to the specified tension.   

323
00:18:27,541 --> 00:18:31,876
♪♪         

324
00:18:31,878 --> 00:18:34,712
next up is the seat assembly. 

325
00:18:34,714 --> 00:18:37,315
he slides the seat stem into the post       

326
00:18:37,317 --> 00:18:43,021
and tightens the adjustment knob to lock it in place.   

327
00:18:43,023 --> 00:18:45,990
he inserts the handlebar post into the bike frame      

328
00:18:45,992 --> 00:18:47,692
and fishes the gear cable   

329
00:18:47,694 --> 00:18:51,563
and communication wires through it.          

330
00:18:51,565 --> 00:18:56,767
he secures the handlebar post with the adjustment knob.   

331
00:18:56,769 --> 00:18:58,969
he connects the communication line     

332
00:18:58,971 --> 00:19:02,807
to the resistance system's computer board.    

333
00:19:02,809 --> 00:19:05,643
he links the gear cable to the resistance system     

334
00:19:05,645 --> 00:19:08,746
and tests its functionality.  

335
00:19:08,748 --> 00:19:13,918
satisfied, he tightens a nut at
the side to secure the cable. 

336
00:19:13,920 --> 00:19:15,953
another worker installs a plastic cover        

337
00:19:15,955 --> 00:19:18,022
on the drivetrain.       

338
00:19:18,024 --> 00:19:21,191
this will protect the cyclist's
legs from the pulley system  

339
00:19:21,193 --> 00:19:25,062
and shield the metal components from human sweat.  

340
00:19:25,064 --> 00:19:28,633
for added moisture protection, she applies sealer around   

341
00:19:28,635 --> 00:19:32,470
a welded reinforcement on the bike frame.       

342
00:19:32,472 --> 00:19:34,205
she then encases the fork of the bike      

343
00:19:34,207 --> 00:19:39,076
with more molded plastic.   

344
00:19:39,078 --> 00:19:44,515
bolts secure the casings to the bike.          

345
00:19:44,517 --> 00:19:48,419
she now places a magnetized microphone on the axle     

346
00:19:48,421 --> 00:19:52,023
and spins the flywheel at a high rpm.         

347
00:19:52,025 --> 00:19:53,725
this is a test.        

348
00:19:53,727 --> 00:19:58,028
the bike must operate noiselessly.          

349
00:19:58,030 --> 00:20:03,000
and the decibel meter confirms the noise level is negligible. 

350
00:20:03,002 --> 00:20:07,104
she also feels the frame for unwanted vibrations.    

351
00:20:07,106 --> 00:20:08,673
she now sets the location of  

352
00:20:08,675 --> 00:20:10,875
the magnetic resistance mechanism           

353
00:20:10,877 --> 00:20:13,277
using a special tool.     

354
00:20:13,279 --> 00:20:15,279
this calibrates the resistance 

355
00:20:15,281 --> 00:20:17,949
so that they handlebar computer can find it      

356
00:20:17,951 --> 00:20:22,286
and display the resistance setting during cycling.    

357
00:20:22,288 --> 00:20:25,889
another member of the team then
applies thread-locking adhesive

358
00:20:25,891 --> 00:20:29,627
to the screw holes in the crank arms.       

359
00:20:29,629 --> 00:20:32,629
he screws the pedals tightly to the crank arms   

360
00:20:32,631 --> 00:20:34,599
and torques them to a specific setting.     

361
00:20:34,601 --> 00:20:38,669
♪♪         

362
00:20:38,671 --> 00:20:41,739
the worker aligns the four bolt holes on the frame    

363
00:20:41,741 --> 00:20:45,108
to the bolts on the base and secures them with cap nuts.

364
00:20:45,110 --> 00:20:48,679
♪♪         

365
00:20:48,681 --> 00:20:53,084
he installs a metal guard that encircles most of the flywheel.

366
00:20:53,086 --> 00:20:55,586
this prevents contact with the edge of the wheel   

367
00:20:55,588 --> 00:20:58,389
when it's spinning.      

368
00:20:58,391 --> 00:21:01,826
once the trip computer has been
mounted to the top of the frame,

369
00:21:01,828 --> 00:21:05,663
he slides the handlebar into place.          

370
00:21:05,665 --> 00:21:07,999
it takes about 2 hours to manufacture         

371
00:21:08,001 --> 00:21:10,068
this stationary bike.     

372
00:21:10,070 --> 00:21:13,137
now that the work is done, the workout can begin.     

373
00:21:13,139 --> 00:21:17,141
♪♪         

